== Ancient methods == {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! '''Method''' !! Description |- | align="center" | [[Animal]]s || * [[Execution by elephant|Crushing by elephant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neatorama.com/2007/05/29/this-wont-hurt-a-bit-a-painlessly-short-and-incomplete-evolution-of-execution/|title=This Won't Hurt a Bit: A Painlessly Short (and Incomplete) Evolution of Execution.|author=|date=|website=neatorama.com}}</ref> * Devouring by animals, as in ''[[damnatio ad bestias]]'' (i.e., as in the [[cliché]], "being thrown to the lions"), as well as by [[alligator]]s, [[crocodile]]s, [[piranha]] and [[shark]]s. * Stings from scorpions and bites by snakes, spiders, etc. (e.g. the "[[Snake pit]]" of Germanic legend){{Dubious|date=September 2012}}<!--We should have at least one non-legendary account in which a person is *sentenced to death* by venomous bite. Otherwise this entry ought to be removed, and sooner than in two years from now.--> * Tearing apart by horses (''e.g.'', in [[Middle Ages|medieval]] Europe and [[History of China#Imperial era|Imperial China]], with four horses; or "[[Hanged, drawn and quartered|quartering]]", with four horses, as in ''[[The Song of Roland]]'' and ''[[Child Owlet]]''). * Trampling by horses (example: [[Al-Musta'sim]], the last [[Abbasid]] [[Caliph]] in [[Baghdad]]). |- | align="center" | Back-breaking || A [[Mongolia]]n method of execution that avoided the spilling of blood on the ground<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFx3OlrBMpQC&pg=PA53&dq=Back+broken+mongol|title=The History of the Mongol Conquests|first=J. J.|last=Saunders|date=1 March 2001|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|via=Google Books|page=53}}</ref> (example: the Mongolian leader [[Jamukha]] was probably executed this way in 1206).<ref>''The Secret History of the Mongols'', book 8, chapter 201.</ref> |- | align="center" | [[Blowing from a gun]]||Tied to the mouth of a cannon, which is then fired. |- | align="center" | [[Blood Eagle]]||Cutting the skin of the victim by the spine, breaking the ribs so they resembled blood-stained wings, and pulling the lungs out through the wounds in the victim's back. Used by the [[Vikings]]. |- | align="center" | [[Boiling to death]]||This penalty was carried out using a large cauldron filled with water, oil, tar, tallow, or even molten lead. |- | align="center" | [[Brazen bull]]||Pushed inside an iron bull statue and then cooked alive after a fire is lit under it. |- | align="center" | [[Breaking wheel]]||Also known as the Catherine wheel, after a [[Saint Catherine of Alexandria|saint]] who was allegedly sentenced to be executed by this method. |- | align="center" | [[Premature burial|Buried alive]]||Traditional [[punishment]] for [[Vestal virgins]] who had broken their vows. |- | align="center" | [[Execution by burning|Burning]]||Most infamous as a method of execution for [[Heresy|heretics]] and [[Witchcraft|witches]]. A slower method of applying single pieces of burning wood was used by [[Indigenous peoples of North America|Native Americans]] in torturing their captives to death.<ref>Frederick Drimmer (ed.) ''"Captured by the Indians - 15 Firsthand Accounts, 1750-1870"'', Dover Publications, Mineola, N.Y., 1985.</ref> |- | align="center" | [[Crushing (execution)|Crushing]]|| By a weight, abruptly or as a slow ordeal. |- | align="center" | [[Disembowelment]]||Often employed as a preliminary stage to the actual execution, e.g. by beheading; an integral part of ''[[seppuku]]'' (''harakiri''), which was sometimes used as a form of capital punishment. |- | align="center" | [[Dismemberment]]|| Being [[drawn and quartered]] sometimes resulted in dismemberment. Note: has been used in combination, such as [[hanged, drawn and quartered]] |- | align="center" | [[Hanged, drawn and quartered|Drawing and quartering]]||English method of executing those found guilty of [[high treason]]. |- | align="center" | [[Falling (execution)|Falling]]||The victim is thrown off a 