comment=Most workers are covered by an [[Industrial award|award]], which may vary by employee age, geographical location and industry. For employees 21+ not covered by an award or agreement, the minimum wages is [[Australian Dollar|A$]]18.93 ($13.44 USD) per hour, or A$719.20 ($510.79 USD) per week; set federally by the [[Fair Work Commission]]. The figures indicated exclude mandatory employer [[Superannuation in Australia|superannuation contributions]] of at least 9.5% of the employee's total annual salary and any extra loadings received (e.g. many employees are entitled to an extra 17.5% of their daily income on days where they take annual leave, penalty rates for work undertaken on weekends and public holidays of up to 200% of their base rate, and the entitlement that non-permanent employees be paid at least 15% higher than the base rate of pay).<br/>Workers under 21, apprentices and trainees not covered by an award each have a minimum wage level set nationally below the official minimum.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.fairwork.gov.au/about-us/policies-and-guides/fact-sheets/minimum-workplace-entitlements/minimum-wages|title=Minimum Wages|accessdate=24 January 2016|publisher=Australian Government|author=Fair Work Ombudsman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairwork.gov.au/pay/national-minimum-wage/Pages/default.aspx |title=National minimum wage – Pay |publisher=Australian Government|author=Fair Work Ombudsman |date= |accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> Minimum wage for workers under 16 is 36.8% of the 21+ minimum wage at [[Australian Dollar|A$]]6.97 ($5) per hour.<ref>{{citation|url=http://awardviewer.fwo.gov.au/award/show/MA000104#P244_22681|accessdate=24 January 2016|title=Miscellaneous Award 2010|publisher=Australian Government}}</ref>}}

